### Foreach Loop in C#

The `foreach` loop iterates over elements in a collection or array without using an index variable.

### Syntax

```csharp
foreach (type variableName in collection)
{
    // Code for each element
}
```

### Basic Example

```csharp
string[] fruits = { "Apple", "Banana", "Cherry" };
foreach (string fruit in fruits)
{
    Console.WriteLine(fruit);
}
```

### With var (Implicit Typing)

```csharp
int[] numbers = { 10, 20, 30 };
foreach (var num in numbers)
{
    Console.WriteLine(num);
}
```

### Foreach with Different Collections

| Collection Type | Example |
|-----------------|---------|
| Array | `foreach (int n in array)` |
| List | `foreach (string s in list)` |
| Dictionary | `foreach (var kvp in dict)` |
| String | `foreach (char c in "hello")` |

### Dictionary Iteration

```csharp
var capitals = new Dictionary<string, string>
{
    { "USA", "Washington" },
    { "France", "Paris" },
    { "Japan", "Tokyo" }
};

foreach (var pair in capitals)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"{pair.Key}: {pair.Value}");
}
```

### for vs foreach

| Aspect | for | foreach |
|--------|-----|---------|
| Index access | Yes | No |
| Modify during iteration | Yes (carefully) | No (throws exception) |
| Readability | More verbose | Cleaner |
| Performance | Slightly faster | Comparable |

### LINQ Integration

```csharp
var evenNumbers = numbers.Where(n => n % 2 == 0);
foreach (var num in evenNumbers)
{
    Console.WriteLine(num);
}
```

### Limitations

```csharp
// Cannot modify collection during foreach
foreach (var item in list)
{
    // list.Remove(item);  // Throws InvalidOperationException
}

// Use for loop instead when modifying
for (int i = list.Count - 1; i >= 0; i--)
{
    if (list[i] % 2 == 0)
        list.RemoveAt(i);
}
```

> **Key Point:** `foreach` provides read-only access to elements. You cannot add or remove items from the collection during iteration. Use `for` when you need index access or need to modify the collection.

### Multiple Enumeration

```csharp
foreach (var item in collection)
{
    foreach (var subitem in subcollection)
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"{item}: {subitem}");
    }
}

codeExample:
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        var scores = new List<int> { 85, 92, 78, 95, 88 };

        Console.WriteLine("Scores:");
        int sum = 0;
        foreach (int score in scores)
        {
            Console.WriteLine($"- {score}");
            sum += score;
        }

        double average = (double)sum / scores.Count;
        Console.WriteLine($"\nAverage: {average:F1}");
    }
}
